^B@2^*BBergen: ^*N|cp||at|When asked what is the most important topic in the play of the cards, the answer that I always give is “managing entries”. On most hands it is very important to have good communication between the two hands. You should be able to get back to a hand later when you need to be there. |
PG| ***** 1 ***** |


AT|

This may involve handling your trumps in a flexible way, leaving entries to both hands. It may involve a decision as to where to win a trick when you have a choice. Too many players think about “where do I want to be now?” when the reality is that the more important decision, on the great majority of hands, is where will you need to be later. It is more difficult to think ahead as opposed to taking care of your decision right now, but it is very necessary. |
PG| ***** 2 ***** |


AT|

The hands in this lesson will be played from an IMP point of view. The goal will be to make your contract without thinking about overtricks. On the few hands where you should play differently at Match Points, because overtricks should be part of your consideration, I will make clear how you should change your play. But for the most part, when you are playing bridge, whether Match Point scoring or IMPs (Swiss Teams, Knockout Teams, etc.), the key is to make your contract. Do not think about overtricks.|
