As we look back over the 15 hands that you have just heard and played, here are some suggestions to keep in mind that will help you when you are playing. One of the key concepts that comes to mind is how much easier it is to make contracts when the strength is evenly divided between the 2 hands. When one hand, whether that hand is the declarer or dummy, has much weaker assets than his partner, playing the hand is usually more difficult. You do want to keep that in mind in the bidding. It is easier to make 3NT with 12 HCP opposite 13 HCP than 20 HCP opposite 6 HCP, even though in the more difficult case you have 1 more HCP. |
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


AT|

Don't be a “grabber”. Losing your losers early is usually the right strategy. Most players do not duck often enough. When you lead a side suit, use up the honors from the short side first. Most people know that. But that does not apply when a defender leads the suit. |
PG| ***** 28 ***** |


AT|

There are also many occasions in the trump suit where you want to keep entries to both hands for later on. Each situation must be dealt with on its own merits. |
PG| ***** 29 ***** |


AT|

Do not get stuck in the short hand. You must be very careful with blocked suits to make sure you maximize your winners in those suits.|
PG| ***** 30 ***** |


AT| 

Be aware of your intermediate cards – tens, nines, and even eights. They can make all the difference in the world. Keep that in mind in the bidding. Those cards should affect the bidding since they will affect the play. |
PG| ***** 31 ***** |


AT|

When you are in no trump and the weaker hand has the suit you want to develop, that is the time when thinking about and preserving entries to the weaker hand is the most crucial. |
PG| ***** 32 ***** |


AT|

